@lilnoosh I just think the conversation should be had in a way that isn’t offensive. How Gillette was framing the situation was that men being despicable and controlled by toxic masculinity is the norm, and telling all men that they need to be better than they are. (I’m not saying there aren’t lots of men out there that need to change though)
But if the ad was made framing all women as despicable misandrist femenazis, and saying women being despicable and ignoring the views of men is the norm, and that the majority of women need to change and be better people, there would be a large outcry of sexism.
And personally I feel this is a good framework to bare in mind when crafting something aimed specifically at those of another gender with the intent of correcting or changing the behaviour of that gender — if it is not a good method of addressing one gender, it will not be a good method of addressing another.
